<h3 id="bushwhacking">Bushwhacking</h3>
<p>Being off trail and wading through shrubs and tall plants is not my idea of fun. I usually go out of my way to avoid it. Besides the general irritation of it, it makes me nervous not to see the ground I'm walking on and the fear that I may fall in a hole and injure myself. But if the reward is worth it, I'll plod on through. The low shrub is not too bad but if it's willow or dense windblown spruce, prepare for a rough time. Luckily, it's easy to get above treeline and sometimes you can avoid the hassle if you can walk along the ridge.</p>
<ul>
	<li><a href="https://www.backpacker.com/trips/tundra-trekking-tips" target="_blank">Tundra Trekking Tips</a></li>
</ul>

<h3 id="post-holing">Post Holing</h3>
<p>Post holing is when you are walking along the top of snow and one or both of your legs sinks in deep without warning. It's a frightening experience and one thing sure to slow you down. If this is a potential where you're hiking, it can be worth the extra weight to bring snowshoes. Depending on the trail, I usually pack them right into mid-June (a very surreal experience to be in snowshoes and shorts). It can be a nuisance if you are going between snow and ground during breakup but better a nuisance than a broken leg. I also started bringing a walking stick (or trekking poles if you prefer) which comes in real handy when you need some leverage to get your leg out of the hole.</p>
<p>If you are hiking early in the season, when the temps are still pretty chilly in the morning, that's when you should hike as the top layer is usually frozen and more secure. In the summer, any snow you travel over should be packed down enough to cause you little trouble.</p>
<ul>
	<li><a href="https://www.backpacker.com/gear/snow-smarts" target="_blank">Snow Smarts: How to Travel Safely Across Four Seasons of White</a></li>
</ul>

<h3 id="alaska-mile">The Alaska Mile</h3>
<p>The "Alaska Mile" is a term used to describe the phenomenon that the perceived distance is often shorter than reality. This is often due to the deceiving mental perception of the contours of a glacial valley. Glacial valleys are often at a very gentle incline, with a number of small ridges. What this means is that you feel like you're walking flat when you are really going up. Also, since you usually see only the immediate ridge in front of you and the top of the valley, you feel like the distance should be shorter. Except, then you get to the top of that ridge and you see the next one.</p>
<p>In winter, the snow and ice reflect the sunlight differently than brush and rock in summer. This reflection gives the illusion that things are closer than they really are. The depth of the snow and ice also effects your perception of distance, as deeper snow makes things look bigger (thus closer) at further distances than more shallow snow.</p>

<h3 id="fording-rivers">Fording Rivers</h3>
<p>On many trails in Alaska, you better be prepared to get your feet wet, as there are often stream crossing that may or may not have a bridge. Just about every one of those streams, creeks and rivers have the melting glaciers as their source which means cold, cold, cold. If you're going to Denali or the Wrangell's, you may have to deal with going in above your waist. Sometimes on the way to your destination, the stream was just a trickle, the next day it's a raging torrent. Many glacial rivers are shallow in the morning and deep in the afternoon due to the glacier melting during warmer daylight hours.</p>
<p>Needless to say, if you have to cross, you need to do it quickly and safely. The best thing to do is take the time and find the best place to cross. It's better to find a spot where the stream or river breaks into may slower sections (known as braided). If you're with a group, cross together and link arms for added stability.</p>
<p><strong>Before crossing, unbuckle all straps and belts on your pack no matter the current or depth.</strong> If you don't and you fall in, a pack can fill with water very quickly, adding significant weight and making it harder for you get to the surface as well as restricting your maneuverability. Mentally prepared to shed your pack quickly if necessary.</p>
<p>Protect your camera and other valuables before you cross. It's usually the ones I thought would be trouble free that I've gotten soaked. I always carry a few extra Ziploc bags to keep things dry.</p>
<p>One of the best articles I've ever read on the subject was in the book <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/0963235931?tag=akhikesearch-20" target="_blank"><em>Beyond Backpacking</em></a> by Ray Jardine. <em>This is a great book in general. I am slowly working toward "lightweight backpacking" and this is the bible on the subject.</em></p>
<ul>
	<li><a href="http://dnr.alaska.gov/parks/safety/rivercross.htm" target="_blank">Be Safe Out There: River Crossings</a></li>
</ul>

<h3 id="scree">Scree</h3>
<p>One thing you may encounter while hiking the mountains and glacial valleys of Alaska is having to climb up or down scree and talus. Scree is the smaller rocks and talus are the boulders and larger rocks. It's not as scary as it looks but you do need to be careful. If possible, try to stay on the side of it for quicker traveling. Never take the next step until you are sure the resting foot is secure.</p>

<h3 id="glaciers">Glaciers</h3>
<p>Glacier travel is only for the experienced. Even for them, it is a dangerous situation. You should never walk out on a glacier. The danger lies in its deep crevasses that are sometimes hidden by snow. There are many people who thought they were on solid ice who found themselves severely injured at the bottom of a crevasse. The people in your party may not be able to extricate you, especially without rope and special equipment. Be very careful at the front, or terminus, of a glacier. Although rare, huge chunks of ice have been known to break off (known as calving) and crush people.</p>
<p>There are 3 glaciers that I know of where you can walk on top near the terminus with minimal risk: Exit Glacier, Matanuska Glacier, and Worthington Glacier.</p>
<p>A great book for the layperson, but hard to find is <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/1555910750?tag=akhikesearch-20" target="_blank"><em>Glaciers of North America: a Field Guide</em></a> by Sue Ferguson. The book also covers the rudiments of glacial travel.</p>
<ul>
	<li><a href="https://nsidc.org/cryosphere/glaciers" target="_blank">All About Glaciers</a></li>
</ul>

<h3 id="mudflats">Mudflats</h3>
<p><strong>Never walk on the mudflats on the banks of the Cook Inlet and Turnagain Arm.</strong> What looks secure is in reality very finely ground silt (the effluent of glacial grinding). The stuff is like quicksand and it is almost impossible to get your feet out of it. With one of the fastest tides in the world, your chances of drowning are very real.</p>
<ul>
